100.title: {sourceType}: Continue
100.description: The server has received the request headers and the client should proceed to send the request body.

101.title: {sourceType}: Switching protocols
101.description: The requester has asked the server to switch protocols and the server has agreed to do so.

102.title: {sourceType}: Processing
102.description: The server has received and is processing the request, but no response is available yet.

201.title: {sourceType}: Created
201.description: The request has been fulfilled, resulting in the creation of a new resource.

202.title: {sourceType}: Accepted
202.description: The request has been accepted for processing, but the processing has not been completed. It might or might not be eventually acted upon, and may be disallowed when processing occurs.

203.title: {sourceType}: Non authoritative information
203.description: The server is a transforming proxy that received a 200 OK from its origin, but is returning a modified version of the origin's response.

204.title: {sourceType}: No content
204.description: The server successfully processed the request and is not returning any content.

205.title: {sourceType}: Reset content
205.description: The server successfully processed the request and is not returning any content.

206.title: {sourceType}: Partial content
206.description: The server is delivering only part of the resource (byte serving) due to a range header sent by the client. The range header is used by HTTP clients to enable resuming of interrupted downloads,or split a download into multiple simultaneous streams.

207.title: {sourceType}: Multi status
207.description: The message body that follows is an XML message and can contain a number of separate response codes, depending on how many sub-requests were made.

208.title: {sourceType}: Already reported
208.description: The members of a DAV binding have already been enumerated in a preceding part of the (multistatus) response, and are not being included again.

226.title: {sourceType}: Im used
226.description: The server has fulfilled a request for the resource, and the response is a representation of the result of one or more instance-manipulations applied to the current instance.

300.title: {sourceType}: Multiple choices
300.description: Indicates multiple options for the resource from which the client may choose (via agent-driven content negotiation).

301.title: {sourceType}: Moved permanently
301.description: This and all future requests should be directed to the given URI

302.title: {sourceType}: Found
302.description: The HTTP/1.0 specification (RFC 1945) required the client to perform a temporary redirect (the original describing phrase was "Moved Temporarily"), but popular browsers implemented 302 with the functionality of a 303 See Other. Therefore, HTTP/1.1 added status codes 303 and 307 to distinguish between the two behaviours. However, some Web applications and frameworks use the 302 status code as if it were the 303.

303.title: {sourceType}: See other
303.description: The response to the request can be found under another URI using a GET method.

304.title: {sourceType}: Not modified
304.description: Indicates that the resource has not been modified since the version specified by the request headers If-Modified-Since or If-None-Match.

305.title: {sourceType}: Use proxy
305.description: The requested resource is available only through a proxy, the address for which is provided in the response.

306.title: {sourceType}: Switch proxy
306.description: No longer used. Originally meant "Subsequent requests should use the specified proxy."

307.title: {sourceType}: Temporary redirect
307.description: In this case, the request should be repeated with another URI; however, future requests should still use the original URI.

308.title: {sourceType}: Permanent redirect
308.description: The request and all future requests should be repeated using another URI.

400.title: {sourceType}: Bad request
400.description: The server cannot or will not process the request due to an apparent client error (e.g., malformed request syntax, too large size, invalid request message framing, or deceptive request routing).

401.title: {sourceType}: Unauthorized
401.description: Similar to 403 Forbidden, but specifically for use when authentication is required and has failed or has not yet been provided

402.title: {sourceType}: Payment required
402.description: Reserved for future use. The original intention was that this code might be used as part of some form of digital cash or micro payment scheme, but that has not happened, and this code is not usually used.

403.title: {sourceType}: Forbidden
403.description: The request was valid, but the server is refusing action. The user might not have the necessary permissions for a resource.

404.title: {sourceType}: Not found
404.description: The requested resource could not be found but may be available in the future. Subsequent requests by the client are permissible.

405.title: {sourceType}: Method not allowed
405.description: A request method is not supported for the requested resource; for example, a GET request on a form that requires data to be presented via POST, or a PUT request on a read-only resource.

406.title: {sourceType}: Not acceptable
406.description: The requested resource is capable of generating only content not acceptable according to the Accept headers sent in the request.

407.title: {sourceType}: Proxy authentication required
407.description: The client must first authenticate itself with the proxy.

408.title: {sourceType}: Request timeout
408.description: The client did not produce a request within the time that the server was prepared to wait. The client MAY repeat the request without modifications at any later time.

409.title: {sourceType}: Conflict
409.description: Indicates that the request could not be processed because of conflict in the request, such as an edit conflict between multiple simultaneous updates.

410.title: {sourceType}: Gone
410.description: Indicates that the resource requested is no longer available and will not be available again.

411.title: {sourceType}: Length required
411.description: The request did not specify the length of its content, which is required by the requested resource.

412.title: {sourceType}: Precondition failed
412.description: The server does not meet one of the preconditions that the requester put on the request.

413.title: {sourceType}: Payload too large
413.description: The request is larger than the server is willing or able to process. Previously called "Request Entity Too Large".

414.title: {sourceType}: Uri too long
414.description: The URI provided was too long for the server to process. Often the result of too much data being encoded as a query-string of a GET request, in which case it should be converted to a POST request. Called "Request-URI Too Long" previously.

415.title: {sourceType}: Unsupported media type
415.description: The request entity has a media type which the server or resource does not support.

416.title: {sourceType}: Range not satisfiable
416.description: The client has asked for a portion of the file (byte serving), but the server cannot supply that portion.

417.title: {sourceType}: Expectation failed
417.description: The server cannot meet the requirements of the Expect request-header field.

418.title: {sourceType}: I am a teapot
418.description: This HTTP status is used as an Easter egg in some websites, including Google.com.

421.title: {sourceType}: Misdirected request
421.description: The request was directed at a server that is not able to produce a response (for example because a connection reuse).

422.title: {sourceType}: Unprocessable entity
422.description: The request was well-formed but was unable to be followed due to semantic errors, perhaps data required by the backend is missing

423.title: {sourceType}: Locked
423.description: The resource that is being accessed is locked.

424.title: {sourceType}: Failed dependency
424.description: The request failed due to failure of a previous request (e.g., a PROPPATCH).

426.title: {sourceType}: Upgrade required
426.description: The client should switch to a different protocol such as TLS/1.0, given in the Upgrade header field.

428.title: {sourceType}: Precondition required
428.description: The origin server requires the request to be conditional.

429.title: {sourceType}: Too many requests
429.description: The user has sent too many requests in a given amount of time. Intended for use with rate-limiting schemes.

431.title: {sourceType}: Request header fields too large
431.description: The server is unwilling to process the request because either an individual header field, or all the header fields collectively, are too large.

451.title: {sourceType}: Unavailable for legal reasons
451.description: A server operator has received a legal demand to deny access to a resource or to a set of resources that includes the requested resource. The code 451 was chosen as a reference to the novel Fahrenheit 451.

500.title: {sourceType}: Internal server error
500.description: A generic error message, given when an unexpected condition was encountered and no more specific message is suitable.

501.title: {sourceType}: Not implemented
501.description: The server either does not recognize the request method, or it lacks the ability to fulfill the request.

502.title: {sourceType}: Bad gateway
502.description: The server was acting as a gateway or proxy and received an invalid response from the upstream server.

503.title: {sourceType}: Service unavailable
503.description: The server is currently unavailable (because it is overloaded or down for maintenance).

504.title: {sourceType}: Gateway timeout
504.description: The server was acting as a gateway or proxy and did not receive a timely response from the upstream server.

505.title: {sourceType}: Http version not supported
505.description: The server does not support the HTTP protocol version used in the request.

506.title: {sourceType}: Variant also negotiates
506.description: Transparent content negotiation for the request results in a circular reference.

507.title: {sourceType}: Insufficient storage
507.description: The server is unable to store the representation needed to complete the request.

508.title: {sourceType}: Loop detected
508.description: The server detected an infinite loop while processing the request.

510.title: {sourceType}: Not extended
510.description: Further extensions to the request are required for the server to fulfill it.
